---
// /compare/ — hub linking every comparison page. Internal-linking + crawl entry
// for the /compare/<slug> set. Prose layout, token-only.
import Prose from '../../layouts/Prose.astro';
import { competitors } from '../../data/compare';
---

<Prose
  title="Compare tela — open-source, self-hosted, AI-native team wiki"
  description="How tela compares to Notion, Confluence, Outline, GitBook, Docmost, BookStack, Wiki.js and more — honestly, including what each still does better."
  kicker="Compare"
  heading="Compare tela with the alternatives"
  updated="June 30, 2026"
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" is:inline slot="head" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    '@context': 'https://schema.org',
    '@graph': [
      {
        '@type': 'CollectionPage',
        '@id': 'https://telawiki.com/compare/#page',
        name: 'Compare tela with the alternatives',
        url: 'https://telawiki.com/compare/',
        inLanguage: 'en',
        isPartOf: { '@id': 'https://telawiki.com/#website' },
        about: { '@id': 'https://telawiki.com/#software' },
      },
      {
        '@type': 'BreadcrumbList',
        itemListElement: [
          { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 1, name: 'Home', item: 'https://telawiki.com/' },
          { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 2, name: 'Compare', item: 'https://telawiki.com/compare/' },
        ],
      },
    ],
  })} />

  <p class="lead">
    tela is an open-source (AGPL), self-hostable, markdown-native team wiki: your
    docs stay as canonical markdown you own, agents read and write them through a
    built-in MCP server, and Atlas generates a cited, coverage-checked wiki from
    your git repos and Jira. Here is how it stacks up against the tools you would
    otherwise reach for — including what each of them still does better.
  </p>

  <ul class="tool-grid">
    {competitors.map((c) => (
      <li>
        <a href={`/compare/${c.slug}/`}>tela vs {c.name}</a>
        <span class="desc">{c.heading}</span>
      </li>
    ))}
  </ul>

  <h2>The short version</h2>
  <p>
    Most of these are good tools. tela's distinct angle is two things: it is
    fully open-source and self-hostable with canonical markdown you own, and
    <strong>Atlas</strong> generates documentation from your code and keeps it
    honest about drift — which most wikis leave entirely to human discipline. A
    built-in MCP server is a strength tela shares with several of them, not a
    monopoly.
  </p>
  <p>
    Try it: self-host under AGPL, or start on the free cloud tier at
    <a href="/">telawiki.com</a>.
  </p>
</Prose>
